metadata.name: Faux #328
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Elevation #122
metadata.description:
There‚Äôs so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

‚Äì

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect‚Äôs elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

‚Äì

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

‚Äì

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: rosarium #183
metadata.description:
"rosarium" is part of the live minting experience at Non Fungible Conference Lisbon, June 7-8, 2023.

Each iteration of rosarium is an arrangement of several unique species of ethereal, alien, and yet familiar flowers.

This piece uses progressive volumetric rendering to produce photorealistic images. It may take several seconds to produce a recognizable image, and several minutes to produce a high-quality render with no visible noise.

Created with webgl and clojurescript.

Controls:

Click on the canvas to open a menu in the top right corner. In this menu you will see controls to capture a screenshot, adjust resolution, and adjust the camera, along with several other controls.

When the "optimized render" option is checked, the page will compute an acceleration structure before rendering to allow the piece to converge much faster. With this option checked, the piece may need to process for up to a minute before rendering begins, but subsequently the rendering will proceed much more quickly than normal. This can be used to generate high-quality captures more quickly than when the option is not checked.

When the "filtering" option is checked, a noise filter will be applied to the result of the render, reducing the appearance of noise.

The "logic multiple" slider can be used to multiply the amount of rendering work done each frame. Increasing this number may allow the piece to render more quickly, but may also make the page laggy. It is not recommended to increase this number unless you have a powerful GPU.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #571

metadata.name: Overshoot #48
metadata.description:
Each day at 2 pm, humanity‚Äôs demand for ecological resources exceeds what earth can regenerate that day. After 2 pm, we live on future generation's expense. This artwork changes to an expressionist version once the overshoot moment has passed, day by day.

This project closes the feedback loop between lifestyle and environmental impact. 10 countries are featured with their individual overshoot moment. In Australia, the resources are completely consumed at 5 am in the morning. In Thailand, the earth‚Äôs ecological limits are reached at about 4 pm. 

The data is based on the Earth Overshoot Day which is hosted and calculated by Global Footprint Network, an international research organization. Find more here: https://www.overshootday.org/newsroom/country-overshoot-days/ 


Press ‚Äòe‚Äô to download the SVG file.

metadata.name: Grove #8
metadata.description:
A generative, impressionist painting of a small grove of trees in one of the four seasons. In spring and summer, flowers bloom in the meadow. A rare variation will create a charcoal drawing on white or black paper. Super rare will create a lighted winter scene that may have a moon behind the tree.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press 's' to save a screenshot at any point. Image size is 1400x1082px.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 3,000 px.

On the paintings only, adding '&bg=true' will stop the painting after the background. Adding '&size=3000&bg=true' will give you a nice desktop background! 

Common Features:
- About 12-14 trees
- One of the four seasons
- One of 12 highlight color tints
- One of 12 shadow color tints
- Varying levels of distance haze
- Varying max brush sizes
- Varying amount of colors in the strokes

Less Common
- 15% chance of a charcoal drawing
- 50% chance it to be a dark winter scene

Rare
- Winter drawing with lights on the tree

Super Rare
- Winter drawing with a moon behind the tree

metadata.name: Balancium #224
metadata.description:
"Balancium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

In the fall of 1931, in Alexander Calder's studio, Marcel Duchamp coined the term 'mobile' for his kinetic sculptures. Later, Calder wrote: "This, in French, means not only 'movable'‚Äî but also a 'motive', 'a reason for an act' so I found it a very good word."
 
Around the same year, Bruno Munari started making colorful and whimsical mobiles. He called them "useless machines", existing without any purpose and inviting viewers to just look. Elements are connected with nearly invisible threads or wires, allowing the artist to create the illusion of shapes floating in the air.

Balancium is both a virtual mobile and a useless object. Generated by the code, it undergoes a continual transformation. The movement of the air, or invisible fluid, becomes an integral part of the design and amplifies serenity. 
 
There is a keyboard key that unlocks more variations.

metadata.name: Tympanic #201
metadata.description:
Tympanic is a companion piece to Euphonic [https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10982] and is released as a free gift to all collectors of Euphonic.

Like Euphonic, this piece attempts to play with the idea of interference and emergent patterns, but this time does so by using pixelation instead of Moire. In this way, where Euphonic was about emergent melodies, Tympanic is about emergent rhythms.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Protein Pelt #332
metadata.description:
An incorrectly placed decimal point led to this pattern. A good friend told me it reminded them of protein structures, I found them to look like animal pelts strewn about.

Each "protein" is made up of 100 pelts, random walking around the canvas from the center. Each "pelt" is made of 5 colors sampled from an array of 84 colors.

Press 's' when in live view to save the image.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #416
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden ‚Äútemplate‚Äù canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‚Äòtemplate‚Äô image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution
